=== Step 3: Audience, Webinar Angle & 3-Pillar Framework ===
{
  "webinar_strategy": {
    "title": "Executive Functioning Reset",
    "promise": "Leave with a clear, realistic weekly reset plan you can run in 30 minutes to reduce missing assignments, last minute cramming, and nightly homework battles (skills based coaching perspective, not therapy, diagnosis, or tutoring).",
    "who_its_for": "Parents and guardians of middle school, high school, and college students who are bright but inconsistent with planning, organization, time management, task initiation, and follow through (ADHD aware, no diagnosis required).",
    "what_they_will_learn": [
      "The 3 most common executive functioning bottlenecks behind missing work (tracking, planning, and starting) and how to spot which one is driving your students patterns",
      "A simple Weekly Reset workflow: missing work audit, deadline capture, and a one page plan for the next 7 days that connects school portals to an actual schedule",
      "How to scaffold without becoming the homework police: prompts that build independence, plus a fade plan so support decreases as skills increase"
    ],
    "bridge_to_offer": "The webinar gives clarity and a quick win (the Weekly Reset you can use immediately). The Executive Functioning Coaching Program provides the full system and implementation support: individualized routines, tools and templates (weekly plan, checklist, portal audit, task breakdown), coached practice with accountability, and a scaffold then fade roadmap so your student can sustain the habits without constant parent monitoring."
  },
  "pillars": [
    {
      "index": 1,
      "title": "Reset Plan",
      "teaches": "How to triage the week: capture every commitment, identify missing work fast, and choose the few highest impact actions for the next 48 hours using a repeatable Weekly Reset routine.",
      "outcome": "Parents stop guessing and students have a clear next step list and a short plan for what must happen first."
    },
    {
      "index": 2,
      "title": "Simple Systems",
      "teaches": "How to build lightweight systems that match school reality: one place to track deadlines, one method to organize materials, and a consistent way to turn assignments into scheduled blocks (with templates and checklists).",
      "outcome": "Fewer lost items and surprise deadlines, with a workable planning and organization setup the student will actually use."
    },
    {
      "index": 3,
      "title": "Follow Through",
      "teaches": "How to convert plans into action: task initiation strategies, time estimation practice, distraction guardrails, and a scaffold then fade approach that shifts responsibility to the student over time.",
      "outcome": "More consistent starts and finishes, less parent conflict, and growing independence week over week."
    }
  ],
  "positioning": {
    "unique_mechanism": "Weekly Reset Workflow with Scaffold Then Fade Coaching",
    "differentiators": [
      "Skills based coaching with clear scope boundaries (not therapy, diagnosis, or tutoring)",
      "Diagnosis not required: executive functioning support framed around practical school and life demands",
      "Concrete artifacts that operationalize the work (weekly reset checklist, portal audit, task breakdown templates, routines playbook)",
      "Parent friendly implementation that reduces micromanaging by design through a planned fade strategy",
      "Focus on sustainable process improvements rather than outcome guarantees"
    ],
    "objection_prebunks": [
      "We tried planners already: the issue is usually the workflow (capture, plan, start), not the planner brand; we teach the routine that makes any tool work",
      "My student wont do it: coaching emphasizes buy in, small starts, and student owned systems rather than parent enforced perfection",
      "We dont have time: the reset is designed to be short and repeatable; consistency beats complexity",
      "Is this tutoring: no, the focus is on planning, organization, and follow through skills that support any class",
      "Is this therapy or ADHD treatment: no, it is educational coaching; referrals to licensed professionals are appropriate for diagnosis or mental health treatment when needed"
    ],
    "tone_notes": "Professional, calm, practical, and non judgmental. Use school reality language (portal, missing work, due dates, backpack, routines). Avoid guarantees and clinical claims; include clear coaching scope and safety disclaimers where appropriate. Hero preview angle: A one page Weekly Reset plan that shows how to go from missing assignments chaos to a clear 7 day schedule."
  }
}


